@NODE 15. "ARexx Commands"

I would rather that you use the AVM Programmer, but here are
the ARexx commands anyway:

@{" Things to note: " Link 15.1.}
@{" Top-level ARexx commands: " Link 15.2.}
@{" Use-mode ARexx commands: " Link 15.3.}
@ENDNODE

@NODE 15.1. "Things to note:"
 o  You must turn on "options results"!  As in:

	OPTIONS RESULTS

 o  The AVM server launches scripts with certain arguments.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 15.2. "Top-level ARexx commands:"
 o  quit -- kills the AVM server

 o  unlisten -- puts the serial port being handled by the server in
    unlisten mode.  This means that there is no pending "read" on the
    serial port.

 o  listen -- makes the AVM server listen to the serial port

 o  closeserial -- closes the serial port

 o  openserial -- opens the serial port

 o  use -- locks the AVM server and puts it in the "use" mode.  See the
    Use-mode ARexx commands.  This is the first thing that you must do
    if you want to do stuff like playvoice, recordvoice, etc.  This
    prevents multiple scripts from fooling around with a single server.

 o  answervoice -- tells the AVM server to launch the script listed in one
    of the "voice call" scripts (if distinctive ring is on, then the
    appropriate one will be launched).

 o  answerfax -- tells the AVM server to launch the script listed in "fax
    script".

 o  answerdata -- tells the AVM server to launch the script listed in
    "data script".

 o  silentanswer -- tells the AVM server to launch the silentanswer.avm
    script.

 o  recordconversation -- tells the AVM server to launch the
    recordconversation.avm script.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 15.3. "Use-mode ARexx commands:"
 o  unuse -- "unlocks" the AVM server and makes it wait for new calls

 o  abort -- stops operations

 o  flushphonebuffer -- AVM remembers DTMF keys when recording and playing
    voice files.  If you do a flushphonebuffer, it makes AVM forget.  This
    is useful if you want to play a voicefile, but when someone presses a
    key, you want to ignore it.

 o  flushbuffers -- Same as flushphonebuffer, but also flushes the serial
    port buffers.

 o  read1key TIMEOUT -- reads 1 DTMF key from the AVM server.  The result
    is placed in the RESULT variable.

	TIMEOUT is a number representing the number of seconds to
        wait before the operation fails

 o  readnkeys N TIMEOUT -- reads N DTMF keys from the AVM server.
    The result is placed in the RESULT variable.

	N is the number of DTMF keys to read
	TIMEOUT is a number representing the number of seconds to
        wait before the operation fails

 o  readkeysuntil KEY N TIMEOUT -- reads at most N DTMF keys from the
    AVM server, or until you get a key specified by KEY.  The result
    is placed in the RESULT variable.

	KEY can be the characters '0', '1', ... '9', '*', '#'
	N is the number of DTMF keys to read
	TIMEOUT is a number representing the number of seconds to
        wait before the operation fails

 o  waitforcharacters TIMEOUT -- waits for characters from the serial
    port until TIMEOUT is reached.  The characters read are in the
    variable RESULT.  This is not very useful.

	TIMEOUT is a number representing the number of seconds to
        wait before the operation fails

 o  writeline STRING -- writes STRING followed by a new-line to the
    serial port.

	STRING is a sequence of characters that you want to send to
        the serial port

 o  readline TIMEOUT -- reads one line from the serial port, or
    terminates if TIMEOUT is reached.  The line read is placed in RESULT.

	TIMEOUT is a number representing the number of seconds to
        wait before the operation fails

 o  dial NUMBER -- causes AVM to dial NUMBER

	NUMBER is any valid telephone number

 o  delay TIMEOUT -- lets the AVM server pause until TIMEOUT is
    reached.

	TIMEOUT is a number representing the number of seconds to
        wait.

 o  requiremode MODE -- tells the AVM server to go into a specific
    mode.

	MODE can take on any of the following values:  COMMAND, VOICE,
        CONNECTED, PLAY, and RECORD.

 o  assumemode MODE -- tells the AVM server to assume it is in a
    specific mode.

	MODE can take on any of the following values: UNKNOWN,
        COMMAND, VOICE, CONNECTED, PLAY, and RECORD.

 o  turnoffvoicemode -- tells the AVM server to turn off voice-mode
    without hanging up.

 o  setserial BPS BITS PARITY STOPBITS HANDSHAKE -- sets the serial
    port configuration

	BPS can take 1200, 2400, 4800, 9600, 19200, 38400, 57600
	BITS can be 7 or 8
	PARITY can be N, E, or O (none, even, odd)
	STOPBITS can be 1 or 2
	HANDSHAKE can be xonxoff, 7wire, or none

 o  requiredevice DEVICE -- tells the AVM server which device to use

	DEVICE can be telephoneline, externalmic, internalspeaker, or
        localhandset.  When dealing with incoming calls, you should use
        telephoneline.

 o  playvoice FILENAME -- tells the AVM server to play the voicefile
    specified by FILENAME

	This returns statuses through the variable RC such as
        KeyDetected, DataDetected, ...  you need to know what actual numbers
        correspond to those statuses.

 o  playbeep FREQUENCY1 FREQUENCY2 DURATION -- tells the AVM server
    to generate a tone (possibly a dual-tone).

	FREQUENCY1 is a number between 0 and 3300 (Hz)
	FREQUENCY2 is a number between 0 and 3300 (Hz)
	DURATION is a number between 0 and 255 (.1 seconds)

 o  recordvoice LENGTH THRESHOLD INTERVAL FILENAME -- tells the AVM
    server to record a voicefile specified by FILENAME.  Recording is
    terminated if LENGTH is reached, silence/quiet is detected (whose
    parameters are specified by THRESHOLD and INTERVAL), tones are
    detected, DTMF is detected, etc.

	LENGTH is a number that indicates the maximum recording time.
        If you put -1 here, this value will be taken from avm:servers.cfg.
	THRESHOLD is a number that indicates the threshold for what
        the modem considers is silent.  Putting a -1 here takes the
        value from avm:servers.cfg.
	INTERVAL is a number that indicates the length of time that
        silence must occur before it is really considered silent.
        Putting a -1 here takes the value from avm:servers.cfg.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------

NOTE:  ANYTHING BELOW THIS LINE IS OLD STUFF.  I HAVE NOT HAD TIME TO
REWRITE IT.  YOU MAY WANT TO LOOK IT OVER THOUGH.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

@ENDNODE

